Breaking: Chinese #Bitcoin and #Ethereum  ETFs launch 9:30am tomorrow - press conference summary is out - here is the translation.👀☝️

Highlights:

- Expected larger first day than USA
- In kind redemptions and subscriptions
- Wallet to wallet transfers
- Mainland Chinese investors are not allowed to invest in Hong Kong’s cryptocurrency spot ETFs
- Hong Kong issuers DO NOT CARE if US Sec declares Ethereum a security.

In this press briefing, Zhu Haokang, head of digital asset management and family wealth of China Asset Management (Hong Kong), and Wayne Huang, head of OSL ETF and custody business, answered the following questions.

Q: What does China Asset Management (Hong Kong) think about the scale of capital inflows on the first day of listing of Hong Kong cryptocurrency ETFs tomorrow?

Zhu Haokang : I am very confident that the trading scale of the Hong Kong virtual asset spot ETF on the first day of listing can exceed the trading scale of the first day in the United States. The issuance scale of the 10 US Bitcoin spot ETF issuers on the first day of January 10 this year was 125 million. US dollar, Hong Kong will exceed US$125 million, and China is confident to become the ETF issuer with the largest trading volume on the first day among the three issuers. The details can be revealed to everyone at 9:30 tomorrow morning.

Wayne Huang : There will be an announcement from the Hong Kong Stock Exchange at 9:30 tomorrow morning, but OSL has indeed completed its first day of raising funds on OSL today with two funds (including ChinaAMC and another fund that cooperates with us). Judging from the numbers, the transactions are indeed far greater than the capital inflow of the U.S. Bitcoin spot ETF on its first day of trading.

Q: What is the difference between Spot China Bitcoin ETF and Spot China Ethereum ETF and other ETFs?

Zhu Haokang : The first difference is that compared with the US spot Bitcoin ETF, we have spot and physical subscriptions and redemptions, which the US spot Bitcoin ETF does not have.

In addition, there are two differences between ChinaAMC's products and the other two: ChinaAMC's Hong Kong spot ETF is the only ETF with Hong Kong dollar, US dollar and RMB counters. The second is that in addition to listed shares, we have unlisted shares. These two points are not available in the other two companies.

Q: In addition to Hong Kong, where else have investors participated in the Hong Kong virtual asset spot ETF?

Zhu Haokang : Thanks to the physical subscription method, first of all, investors include Bitcoin mines, etc. They can use their Bitcoin holdings to directly purchase virtual asset spot ETFs in Hong Kong. Secondly, in countries and regions that have not yet issued ETFs outside of Hong Kong, such as Singapore and the Middle East, we have also come into contact with a large number of investors who are extremely interested. In addition, although the current spot Bitcoin ETF market in the United States is very large, compared with the United States, Hong Kong uses cash and physical subscriptions and is open for trading during Asian trading hours, which will still attract many American investors. Finally, several family offices in Asia and overseas are also very interested in spot crypto ETFs.

Q: Is there currently only one securities firm, Victory Securities, qualified to conduct relevant transactions in physical subscriptions?

Wayne Huang : Not only Victory Securities can do physical subscription, but also Huaying Securities with the support of OSL. Currently, there are three securities firms that can do physical subscription, and there will be more follow-up later. Therefore, after the ETF is listed tomorrow, many brokers will follow up, and it is possible that more brokers will participate in the entire ecosystem of virtual asset ETFs in May.

Q: What are the specific operations for physical purchase?

Wayne Huang : Physical subscription is a pioneering initiative for Hong Kong ETFs that is different from US ETFs. First, the brokerage firm needs to upgrade its No. 1 license to be able to handle virtual asset transactions. Investors can transfer their coins to OSL through this brokerage firm, and then finally transfer their equity back to OSL. Transfer it to the fund's custody account and complete the entire process of physical subscription.

Q: What is OSL’s anti-money laundering process in physical subscription? Is it acceptable for the counterparty to be the wallet of the other exchange?

Wayne Huang : First, investors must connect to OSL through a brokerage firm to open an account. We will perform a whitelist verification on the wallet that is about to transfer money to prove that this wallet is held and controlled by the investor. Second, we will verify the investment. The user's private wallet must be screened to see if there are any suspicious transactions in the wallet's past dozens of transactions on the chain. Only wallets that have passed the whitelist verification can allow him to transfer money.

Can a wallet be the wallet of another exchange? In theory, this can be done. If the anti-money laundering rules of the other exchange are consistent with the OSL rules, we can accept the other party's transfer of coins, but we need the other exchange to provide certain customer information.

Q: Can Hong Kong’s cryptocurrency spot ETFs be open to mainland investors? Or will there be a possibility of opening it up to mainland investors in the future?

Zhu Haokang : Currently, mainland Chinese investors are not allowed to invest in Hong Kong’s cryptocurrency spot ETFs. Hong Kong’s qualified investors, institutional investors, retail investors, and international investors that meet the regulations can all invest in cryptocurrency spot ETFs. For details, you can consult brokers and sales channels, and continue to pay attention to whether there are corresponding regulatory adjustments or the introduction of a specific regulatory framework in the future.

Q: Hong Kong’s Ethereum spot ETF is the first in the world, but if the United States finally determines that “Ethereum” is a security, will it affect Hong Kong’s Ethereum spot ETF?

Wayne Huang : Probably not, because whether the United States defines Ethereum as a security does not affect the independent decision-making of the Hong Kong Securities Regulatory Commission. The Hong Kong Securities Regulatory Commission has its own set of procedures for determining whether a certain virtual asset is a security and whether it can be opened to retail traders. It will not be affected by different opinions between various departments in the United States, or ultimately their own unilateral definition. to Hong Kong.

I also want to emphasize why Hong Kong can be the first in the world to launch an Ethereum spot ETF, rather than the United States? The regulation of cryptocurrency in the United States has multiple departments speaking out at the same time, or trying to regulate it. Who should supervise cryptocurrencies in Hong Kong has long been decided, namely the China Securities Regulatory Commission. The China Securities Regulatory Commission has given some very clear regulatory frameworks. Hong Kong has already had a clear definition of Ethereum. Ethereum It is not a security, but the first non-securities virtual asset to be included in Hong Kong supervision together with Bitcoin, and it is one of the two targets that can be provided to retail investors.

Q: Will Hong Kong launch other virtual asset ETFs?

Wayne Huang : Only Bitcoin and Ethereum for now. We have repeatedly discussed with the China Securities Regulatory Commission the process of how to list coins in compliance transactions in Hong Kong. Let me share briefly. First, we need the issuer of the virtual asset or ourselves to find a legal opinion stating whether the coin is a security or a non-security. And turn the legal opinion and our due diligence on the currency into a detailed research report and submit it to the China Securities Regulatory Commission. After final approval by the China Securities Regulatory Commission, it will be first opened to professional investors. When a certain level of liquidity is reached, it will be included. After a period of time within the scope of an index, we can apply to the China Securities Regulatory Commission to upgrade the currency to be available for retail trading.

I teach you about markets. The market doesn't care if you bought higher. The market doesn't care if you are under water. If you bought #Ethereum at $5k and now it's $3k, the market don't care. Don't click links in responses, imposters. But you see, after you might have bought at $5k, someone else literally bought at $1,000. So while you might cry and whine like a wimp at $3k, they're quite happy here at $3k, because they did 3x while you did -40%. 

So who should new people be more concerned with? The crying, whining, down for 889 days guy that bought at $5k, or the guy that 3x'd by buying 672 days ago? When people buy things, they often do so emotionally, and they prefer good emotions to bad emotions.

What do you think feels better to a new guy? Hearing someone crying and moaning that they personally bought higher? Or hearing about the mad gains of someone that 3x'd his stack? You are participating in the most volatile price action to ever exist, there's always going to be top buyers. Period. And there's always someone that made money selling them that top. Most people just wish the top seller was them.

It's funny that people push the price up themselves with their bids, but don't see that they personally are part of the reason there was a top when there was, because instead of waiting and buying dips, the bought tips. Personal responsibility is quite rare these days. No raindrop thinks it's the flood.

The same goes for sellers. People that sell all the time and never buy yell and scream about others not buying.

Anyway, I sat through #Bitcoin going from $30 to $2, and I'm still here.

TLDR; While you might have bought higher and are sad, many might have bought lower and are happy. It's too bad top buyers yell so much louder than bottom buyers, it's noisy for the new folk.

Not financial advice. Past performance is no guarantee of future.

Latest on HK spot Bitcoin ETFs: They have been approved to exist but not launch (yet). Rumor has it launching next wk so to not compete w Dubai conf. Don't expect a lot of flows (I saw one estimate of $25b that's insane). We think they'll be lucky to get $500m. Here's why:

4. The fees on these likely to be bt 1-2%. Nowhere near the dirt cheap fees in the US "Terrordome"

The reason why #Solana has problems is a certain form of centralization.

Let me explain. 

All blockchain networks can in principle be flooded with transactions. There is no difference between #Bitcoin, #Cardano, Solana, or #Ethereum.

The point is, that the goal of a distributed network is to remain operational and available to users even if a few nodes become suddenly unavailable for any reason.

In the case of client-server architecture, if the only available server is flooded with transactions (requests), it can become unavailable or only provide services to a limited number of users.

If all clients connect to a single server, the server represents a single point of failure.

Solana behaves similarly in that transactions are constantly pushed to leader validators. 

The network does not distinguish between transactions initiated by bots and those initiated by users. That is ok.

A problem is that all users, regardless of their geographical location or the wallets they use, may have a small chance of success in submitting a transaction when Solana is congested.

The reason is that although the validators alternate according to the schedule in the production of blocks, they are constantly flooded with new transactions from RPC nodes.

Transaction flow is directed to a single location on the network. The network is constantly creating another single point of failure for itself.

In a distributed network, there should ideally be no single point of failure. Such a network should be more resilient to transaction overload than a regular server.

Clients (users) can connect to any node in the network and submit transactions through it. Nodes should be somewhat independent from others. 

Most attempts to submit transactions should succeed as more independent nodes are involved.

However, Solana seems to create a single point of failure, which is the validators scheduled to produce the next block. It is a server-like approach.

If the current validator is congested, all users suffer. 

There is no alternative where to submit transactions to the system.

Imagine that one node is overwhelmed with valid spam transactions from bots. 

It should have minimal impact on other nodes if a sufficient number of user transactions enter the system through them. 

If a bot wanted to spam transactions to all nodes, it would have to establish a connection with all of them.

However, in the case of Solana, it is enough for the bots to spam several RPC servers.

The Solana team has implemented several network upgrades to better handle high traffic. It includes adding support for QUIC, stake-weighted QoS, and localized fee markets, etc. It did not help much.

I saw a comment that the current problem is caused by a bug in the implementation of throttling.

Throttling can help manage network traffic but it’s not a silver bullet solution. 

It is a challenge to implement throttling in a blockchain network in a way that maintains the network’s decentralization and security.

The blockchain must be decentralized. Meaning it doesn't have a central authority that can control the rate of transactions.

Implementing throttling usually requires some form of centralized control, which goes against the principle of decentralization. 

It's difficult to implement throttling in a way that is fair to all users.

That's why I think Solana has a design flaw. 

It's not just a bug that can be quickly fixed. This will only be a temporary solution and does not solve the centralization problem.

The resilience of the network must be based on the distributed nature of the blockchain.

Networks that use a mem-pool and allow nodes to pull transactions from other nodes on-demand only if there is room in their mem-pool can be more resistant to similar problems. 

Cardano is an example of this approach.

Although for some users the network may be unavailable if they submit transactions through a node that is overwhelmed with transactions, other users may not suffer from this problem at all.

If a node has a sufficient supply of transactions, it has no reason to pull (download) transactions from another node that may have spam transactions in the mem-pool.

Pull transactions on demand by nodes is a more resilient strategy than pushing transactions in one direction (and thus making a weak point).

I understand why Solana is designed this way. 

The team wanted to make a fast network. However, at the same time, the team sacrificed decentralization and security. 

In other words, Solana does not solve the blockchain trilemma.

There are two primary reasons why Solana may drop 75% of user transactions:

➡️ Transaction fees that are too cheap can lead to the network being easily overwhelmed with valid transactions, such as those attempting arbitrage. Both users and bots typically pay between $0.001 and $0.005 per transaction.

➡️ Solana aims to process all submitted transactions as swiftly as possible, which can result in validators being overwhelmed with transactions.

My primary focus is on the network architecture, as I believe there is a design flaw present.

Here’s an overview of a #Solana transaction’s lifecycle:

➡️Users initiate transactions through their wallet.

➡️The wallet sends the transaction to a RPC server/node. RPC servers can be run by any validator.

➡️The RPC server checks the leader schedule and forwards the transaction to the current leader as well as the next two leaders. The leader is in charge of producing a block for the current slot and is assigned four consecutive slots.

➡️Once the transaction reaches the current leader, the leader validates the transaction's signature and performs other pre-processing steps before scheduling the transaction for execution. 

See Figure 1.

Let's first explain how the validator node works.

For a transaction to be included in a block and permanently recorded in the ledger, it must traverse two underlying layers:

➡️ The network layer
➡️ The consensus layer

Initially, the transaction is processed by the network layer. If it successfully meets the validation criteria of this layer, it proceeds to the consensus layer. 

The consensus layer is tasked with determining the contents of new blocks and achieving agreement on the block across all nodes in the network.

See Figure 2.

The present issue with Solana is that transactions aren't even making it from the network layer to the consensus layer. 

The network layer is so congested (flooded by new arriving transactions) that the node opts to drop a portion of the transactions. 

A node safeguards itself from becoming overloaded and potentially crashing, which could occur due to resource depletion.

Most systems on the network behave this way.

In certain blockchains where transactions exhibit non-deterministic behavior, a transaction can pass through to the consensus layer and still fail afterward. 

The reasons for this can vary.

For instance, the conditions for executing a smart contract transaction according to the user's expectations may not be fulfilled. So the transaction is executed but fails even though the user has paid the fee.

A user transaction may fail due to being overtaken by a bot transaction.

Consider a scenario where out of 100 transactions, 10 are from users and 90 are from bots.

If a node decides to drop 30% of transactions, it is possible that all user transactions could be dropped at a given time.

If a node is overloaded, it may decide to drop even more transactions. Commonly, it is 50% of transactions.

The Solana network is operational and the computational resources of the nodes aren’t depleted due to the dropping of transactions.

As a result, there’s no need for a network restart and the risk of a node crash is low.

The main problem lies in the difficulty users face when trying to submit transactions. 

Despite the network being running, it’s essentially unusable. 

See Figure 3. Only a few bot-generated transactions get to the consensus layer. All user transactions are dropped.

It’s important to note that while each user typically has a single connection for submitting a transaction, bots can maintain multiple connections simultaneously. This gives bots a significant advantage.

Moreover, it's common for a single bot to send spam transactions to multiple nodes (via RPC servers).

This is because bots aim to have their transactions processed as quickly as possible, and sending transactions to multiple nodes increases the likelihood of this happening.

When a Solana node drops a transaction, the transaction fee is not paid. This is because the transaction fee is only incurred when a transaction is successfully processed and included in a block. 

If a transaction is dropped before it reaches the consensus layer, it is as if the transaction was never submitted, and thus no fee is charged.

In Solana, both users and bots connect to validators through RPC servers. 

These servers forward transactions to the current and next two other validators based on a pre-determined leader schedule. 

Unlike other networks that use a mem-pool, Solana transactions are sent directly as a UDP packet to the leaders of the consensus protocol. 

Solana aims to process all submitted transactions as promptly as possible. 

Instead of diffusing transactions to all nodes, which can delay their processing, transactions are directed to the next validators with the expectation that they will all be included in the next blocks.

If an RPC server fails to send a transaction to a validator, it attempts to rebroadcast it. 

The RPC nodes will continue to forward transactions to leaders every two seconds until the transaction is finalized or its block hash expires. 

If the outstanding rebroadcast queue size exceeds 10,000 transactions, new transactions are dropped to prevent the system from being overwhelmed.

For Solana nodes, the occasional overwhelming of an RPC node is not an issue. 

Dropping transactions safeguards the validators. 

However, validators can become overwhelmed by transactions, especially when multiple RPC nodes rebroadcast transactions simultaneously.

See Figure 4.

This can occur if several RPC servers try to rebroadcast transactions to the same validator (or a few of them) according to the schedule. 

Validators are particularly vulnerable to bot attacks via a limited number of RPC servers. 

In the first phase, bots flood several RPC nodes. In the second phase, all RPC nodes trying to rebroadcast transactions flood the scheduled validators.

The Solana team faces a difficult challenge. If transactions are cheap and the network tries to direct them all to several nodes at a given moment, there is always a risk of them being dropped.

Next time I will explain why #Cardano is more resistant to this problem and what is the point of distributed mem-pool.

#Bitcoin is going to $1,900,000 per #BTC because of this #Ethereum DISASTER. 👀

Why? 🤔

The problem with #Ethereum is NOT how many ETH tokens are issued.

The problem with #Ethereum is that the number of tokens that can be issued may be changed at all.

The #Ethereum Foundation is the #Ethereum Central Bank.

I'm not anti-ETH... I'm anti-central bank... If ETH decided to not have a central bank, I'd have no problem with it.

HOWEVER... who decides to dissolve the central bank, the central bank? If the central bank (or the masses) has the power to destroy itself then does it not have the power to re-create itself? 🤔

If a monetary system CAN be exploited it inherently WILL be exploited. 🤷‍♂️

The reason #Bitcoin works is because it had no central bank, foundation, or CEO from the beginning and was designed to not be possible to create. This is what many call the "monetary immaculate conception."

Either your monetary system is controlled by humans, or it is not.

This is binary.
Yes or no.
0 or 1.

ETH policy is a "yes" to human oversight. 🟥
#BTC policy is a "no" to human oversight. 🟩

Many supporters of #Ethereum think #Bitcoin enthusiasts are being needlessly negative about "ETH updates" because #BTC advocates simply "don't understand" a given new gizmo is better...

It doesn't matter if it is "better"... The fact you can determine what is "better" or "worse" is the problem in of itself.

You cannot innovate new changes into improvement when the precise problem you should've been solving in the first place is to achieve immutability where the need to change is irrelevant.

I am not "hating on #Ethereum" baselessly.

If the #Ethereum people loved #Ethereum so much, they wouldn't change it so much... as their actions of changing it are precisely what doom it.

Facts:

✅ETH had a pre-sale of tokens

✅ETH has ability to censor transactions
✅largest ETH stakeholders have largest vote
✅core developers haven't been comfortable staking ETH
✅ETH foundation invites CBDC as "adoption"
✅ETH has changed monetary policy numerous times
✅ETH changed consensus from POW to POS

In summary... I don't blindly subscribe to the "#Bitcoin cult" instead I have conviction that single points of failure are inexcusable.

#BTC may have single points of failure, however I'm yet to see any.

ETH on the other hand has numerous single points of failure, and this "improvement" proposal from a single point of failure to reduce the risk of single points of failure is both ironic and useless.

In summary:.. #Ethereum is a political currency system and the #Ethereum Foundation is the central bank of political power in the system.

WHY does this mean #Bitcoin is super cheap? 📈

The addressable market for a monetary system outside human control is theoretically infinitely larger than one with human control. 🤯

Example: the addressable market for the metric system is 100x larger than the cubit system.

#Ethereum is currently valued at $400 billion. (Perhaps one could argue ETH has some use if they decided to trust the people behind it.) The Ethereum cubit system works as long as you trust the members to be honest about the length of their forearm...

Let's upgrade to metric.

If #Bitcoin as a system of measure were to be worth 100x more than ETH that is a $40 trillion market cap... or $1,900,000 per #Bitcoin.

FORGET all other digital tokens.
FORGET gold, silver, and land.
FORGET all political currency systems.

Simply by this principle of ETH market cap alone, one realizes how incredibly undervalued #Bitcoin is.

This is not to say that ETH is going to zero anytime soon, nor is it to say #Bitcoin is going to $1.9 million soon.

This is to say that if a "digital network" with single points of failure can be pumped up to $400 billion, how dramatically could #BTC be revalued upwards?

If the ETH "cubit" system (which is only one of many) can be valued at $400 billion, how extremely undervalued is the metric system? 🤔

The metric system works because it is a specific fraction of the speed of light. The number is irrelevant, the constant (light speed) is all that mattes.

Likewise the number of #Bitcoin monetary units is irrelevant... The only thing that matters is finite immutability that we don't technically know how to change.

We know how to stop an asteroid from hitting the planet. We don't yet have the technology to crack #Bitcoin immutability... Read that again. 🚀

When people realize the length of a meter (while arbitrary) cannot change they will understand that measurement system is worth orders of magnitude more than cubits.

I wish the users of the #Ethereum cubit system all the best but I hope they understand the metric-maxis are not resentful of their cubit system in particular... They are against human-run measurement systems as a whole. 🖨️

#Bitcoin will trend up in all political currency systems with single points of failure indefinitely. The fact political currency systems (like ETH, Peso, or Dollar) are still valued so highly only highlights the undervaluation of #Bitcoin.

If you adopt the system without single points of failure and you succeed at eliminating your personal single points of failure... you are set.
